title: For Sale:  1943 matching numbers Mosin-Nagant with all the accessories
postcontent:
A very nice condition Mosin-Nagant 91/30 with all visible numbers matching (barrel, bolt, magazine and buttstock plate) and an excellent bore.   This is a 1943 rifle that appears to have been made at the Izhevsk plant (arrow in triangle) and that also carries a hammer & sickle stamp. It does have a discreet Century import marking as well.I have not done any "Bubba" work on this, so it is as originally purchased. The stock is in remarkable condition for its age, showing just a few dings, as well as some flaking of the varnish used by the Soviets on their stocks. Some of the Mosin-Nagants imported in later years were in more rustic shape, but this one is very nice. You will also get many accessories with the gun and all are in great shape. These include a bayonet, a period-correct leather and canvas sling, an oil/solvent bottle, ammunition pouches and a canvas tool bag with all the tools.
I also have 220 rounds of 7.62x54R Soviet ammo that I will sell for an additional $90 (about 41 cents a round). These are the original copper washed rounds manufactured by Soviet bloc countries and that came in spam cans -- these rounds work well in the Mosin and in my opinion are better than the plain steel commercial rounds that can be hard to extract.
Face to face sale to MN resident. Must have PTP or PTC and sign a bill of sale. I would be willing to travel (within reason - i.e. southern Metro, Rochester, Mankato) to meet a serious buyer. Reply via e-mail. I will remove this ad when sold.
P.S. Lowballers will be ignored, as will people who ask if the gun is still available.

This is an AA Arms Pistol, model AP-9, manufactured from 1991 until 2001 in Indian Trail, North Carolina. It is a direct descendant and copy of the notorious Intratec KG-9 from the late 1970s. This was, to the best of our knowledge, the final clone of the KG-9. The KG-9 stirred up some action and warnings from the BATF, an agency that has always been more patient than many of us give them credit for, because that pistol fired from an open bolt. The KG-99 and this pistol, the AP-9, will release the sear from a bolt position that is only about halfway open. While the Intratecs had aluminum alloy lower frames, this one has a rough textured polymer lower frame. It is more ornage than its predecessor, with larger sights and a grooved muzzle barrel instead of a threaded barrel. Weight empty is about 3 1/2 pounds.
